<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> pulled from The Safehouse off a thread about resists</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Paschendale: that sounds like bad luck. Even on deep red mobs I haven't seen that much difference in damage done by aoe's. In fact, I have seen no difference in damage done between people with 175 resist and 500, and I've done quite a bit of testing.<br>
<br>
What I have done in the past is /log the aoe messages for who gets hit by an aoe blast when we fight a mob. Then afterwards I will parse that data and get a list of everyone that got hit by the aoe, and how many times it hit them. Then I would ask people what their resists were at during the fight, and compare that to the chart. Once the resist level gets to 175 or so there wasn't any regular difference in the amount of aoe's that were resisted.<br>
<br>
Sometimes someone with 300+ resist will resist LESS than someone with 150 resist. It's quite random. But over time, doing multiple parses, there isn't any significant variance between 175 and 300+. It's because sometimes someone with tons more resists will resist less than someone with much lower resists that causes people to think that high resists are bugged. They aren't bugged, resists are just random, and high resists don't help.<br>
<br>
Even in a single group it's easy to see the lack of effect from high resists. Often some of the people in the group will move out of song range (rogues especially, trying to stay behind the mob). At times, talking to the group afterwards, they took less damage without song than those that had it. At other times, they took more. It's very random. But again, after lots of samples, the resists just don't seem to matter.<br>
<br>
In ToV it can be different. Many people don't wear resist gear there. If someone is well under 100 resist, and you give them over 100 resist, then the effect is noticeable.<br>
<br>
Even if high resists did matter...the amount of damage the extra bard resists save has to be GREATER than the amount that a cleric in that spot could heal. It has to be great enough not only for the bard to be used instead of a cleric, but for the bard to be carried through non-aoe events when they subtract, not add, to the group.<br>
<br>
Yes, in the old days, when 50 in a resist was considered good, and the only mobs anyone fought were Nagafen and Vox...bards were good. But now, when it's not only possible but not very hard to get 200 in multiple resists WITHOUT buffs...no, bards are not good.<br>
<br>
It's not just resists that hurt bards. It's resists, and low bard melee damage, and haste not stacking, and slowdowns not stacking, and bard buffs working on the bard's group only, and bard songs having very limited range, and everything else that adds up to make bard songs effectively useless on raids.<br>
<br>
Of all the mobs we fight, there is only one where we want a bard, and that's for CT. He's hard to pull without a bard, and occlusion is needed to land slow. We can kill CT without a bard (we don't need to land slow), but a bard helps. Even then, one, and only one, bard is wanted, and that bard is wanted only for that one fight.<br>
<br>
--Thott<br>
